      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Great question! While the primary goal is indeed to capture the highest rate, there are a few other factors to keep in mind when a large chunk of cash sits in one place.\n\nFirst, **liquidity** is a major concern for emergency funds. You want to be able to access the money quickly if you need to cover an unexpected expense, so make sure the high-yield account offers easy withdrawals or at least a reasonable penalty for early withdrawal. Some accounts have a 1% fee for withdrawals before 30 days, which can eat into your interest earnings.\n\nSecond, **inflation** can erode the purchasing power of your savings. Even if you choose the highest rate, you should compare the APY to the current inflation rate to ensure you’re actually growing your money. A quick check: if inflation is 3% and your APY is 4.8%, you’re effectively gaining 1.8% in real returns.\n\nThird, consider **account fees** and **minimum balance requirements**. Some high-yield accounts charge a monthly maintenance fee or require a minimum deposit that could offset your interest gains. Since you’re moving $15,000, make sure the fees are negligible compared to the",
